 # Your brain is erasing your dreams on purpose — and that erasure is the point                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 🌙 15-minute read — written for the first quiet moment of your morning, or the hour before you try to sleep.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 In the spring of 1983, Francis Crick was sitting in his office at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, staring at the Pacific Ocean through the floor-to-ceiling windows that made the building feel like a ship perpetually setting out to sea. He was sixty-seven years old. He had already won the Nobel Prize — thirty years earlier, for the double helix — and he had recently done the thing that only the very secure or the very restless do after a triumph of that magnitude: he had walked away from it entirely and started over in a field he knew almost nothing about.                                                                                                         +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 He had turned to the brain. Specifically, to sleep. More specifically, to dreams.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Crick was not a man who tolerated mystery politely. He had a way of looking at a problem that his colleagues described as almost violent in its directness — he would find the load-bearing assumption underneath an entire field's consensus and kick it until something cracked. And as he read through the dream literature in the early 1980s, something began to bother him in exactly that way.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Everyone was asking what dreams meant. Freudians, Jungians, cognitive psychologists, newly minted neuroscientists who had stumbled into the field through the side door of REM research — they were all, in their different vocabularies, asking the same question: what is the brain trying to say?                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Crick thought they were asking the wrong question entirely.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 He had been reading the work of a British mathematician named Graeme Mitchison, who was thinking about something called attractor networks — computational models of how memory gets stored when neurons fire together repeatedly. And Mitchison had noticed something interesting about these networks: they had a flaw. Feed them too much information over time, and they began to misfire. They would retrieve the wrong memory in response to a cue. They would blur distinct things together. They would start making connections that weren't really there — confabulations, the neuroscientists called them. Hallucinations, in everyday language.                                            +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The networks, in other words, behaved exactly like an overloaded human mind.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Crick pulled out a fresh sheet of paper. He started writing.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 ## The brain that has to unlearn something every night                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 What Crick and Mitchison published in the journal Nature in July of 1983 was not a gentle hypothesis. It was a provocation, stated in the flat declarative style that Crick preferred, the style that made people either immediately convinced or immediately furious.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The function of REM sleep and dreaming, they argued, is not to consolidate memory, process emotion, or communicate wisdom from the unconscious. It is the opposite. The function of dreaming is to weaken certain neural connections — to erase parasitic memories, spurious associations, and the neural noise that accumulates during the day like sediment in a river. They called it reverse learning. Or, in the phrase that made the paper impossible to forget: unlearning.                                                                                                                                                                                                                    +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The dreaming brain, on this account, is not a library. It is a janitor. It moves through the corridors of the day's experience and quietly takes down things that were posted in the wrong place. It dissolves the association between two things that happened to occur simultaneously but have no meaningful relationship. It clears out the attractors that don't deserve to be attractors.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 And then — and this was the part that stopped readers cold — Crick and Mitchison made a prediction that followed logically from the theory but that felt, on first reading, almost impolite.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 If dreaming is the act of erasure, they wrote, then the ideal outcome of a good night of dreaming is that you remember none of it.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 "We dream in order to forget," Crick wrote. The sentence is only six words. It has appeared in neuroscience papers, philosophy papers, popular books, and late-night arguments ever since.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The implication was unsettling for a culture that had spent most of the twentieth century being told that dreams were the royal road to the unconscious, that they contained symbolic truths worth decoding, that forgetting them was a kind of loss. Crick was saying: no. Forgetting them is the delivery mechanism. Forgetting them is the whole point.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Not everyone agreed. The dream research community pushed back, hard and fast. But something had shifted. The question was no longer only what dreams mean. Now it was also what they do — and whether meaning and function were even the same thing.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 ## What the neurons are actually doing at 3am                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 To understand why Crick's theory holds up as well as it does — and it has held up, in modified form, in ways that even its critics now acknowledge — you need a brief detour into how memories get stored in the first place.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 During the day, your brain is constantly forming associations. You hear a song and feel briefly sad without knowing why, and somewhere in your hippocampus a connection is being cemented between that melody and something you have not consciously thought about in years. You see a face and feel a flicker of distrust before you have said a word, and your amygdala has already retrieved a pattern that matches something old and threatening. You learn your colleague's name and your brain hooks it to her red jacket and her laugh and the way she said "actually" before disagreeing with you in the meeting.                                                                             +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This is memory formation at its most basic: synaptic strengthening. Neurons that fire together wire together, as the neuroscientist Donald Hebb formulated it in 1949. The more often two neurons activate in sequence, the stronger the connection between them.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The problem, as Mitchison had observed in his network models, is that this process is not selective. It does not distinguish between a connection that is meaningful and one that is accidental. If two things happen near each other in time, the brain will begin to associate them, whether or not they have anything to do with each other.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 By the end of a full day of living — of receiving, processing, and storing — the network has become cluttered. It contains genuine memories, important associations, hard-won skills. But it also contains noise: spurious links, coincidental pairings, low-quality associations that, if left to strengthen overnight, would begin to interfere with the clean retrieval of the real thing.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This is where REM sleep enters. What the research of the last four decades has shown — most recently in work by Penelope Lewis at Cardiff University and Matthew Walker at UC Berkeley — is that REM sleep is a period of intense neural activity that is specifically calibrated to do something paradoxical: fire neurons in patterns that are uncoupled from real sensory input, which allows the brain to test its connections without the anchoring weight of external reality.                                                                                                                                                                                                                  +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The dreaming brain is, in a very real sense, running simulations. It is replaying fragments of the day, but scrambled — combined with old memories, distorted by the absence of the neurochemicals (specifically, norepinephrine) that normally keep the signal clean and the sequence logical. And what that scrambling appears to do, at the synaptic level, is selectively weaken the weakest connections. The ones that don't have a strong enough root in genuine experience to survive the distortion.                                                                                                                                                                                          +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The strong connections — the ones that matter, the ones tied to real learning — survive the noise. The noise itself dissolves.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This is not the same as simple forgetting. It is more precise than that. It is, as Crick intuited, something closer to editing.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Connecting this to what Michel Jouvet found in 1959 — the discovery that REM sleep involves the brainstem's active suppression of the motor system, covered in Issue 013 — the picture becomes richer. The body is paralyzed. The sensory inputs are blocked. The norepinephrine is withdrawn. All of this, together, creates a contained environment in which the brain can fire intensely without the session becoming chaotic. It is a controlled burn. The forest burns, but the roots hold.                                                                                                                                                                                                      +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 ## The molecule that makes forgetting possible                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Here is where the neurochemistry becomes important — and where the story connects to something you may have already noticed about your own nights.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 In 2019, a neuroscientist named Dheeraj Roy at MIT published research that refined and extended what Crick had proposed. Roy and his team were investigating a particular class of memory — what they called "silent engrams," memories that are stored but cannot be retrieved. They found that during REM sleep, the hippocampus engages in a process of synaptic downscaling: it does not simply erase certain memories, but reduces the gain on them — lowers the volume, so that the signal is still technically present but no longer loud enough to be heard over the rest of the network.                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 What makes this possible, Roy's team found, is the absence of a specific neuromodulator during REM sleep. That neuromodulator is norepinephrine.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 During waking hours, norepinephrine — the same molecule involved in the stress response, the fight-or-flight cascade — acts as a kind of signal amplifier. It sharpens attention, raises the salience of stimuli, and helps the brain tag experiences as important enough to remember. Without it, the brain struggles to form new memories efficiently. With too much of it, the brain cannot stop forming them.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 During REM sleep, the locus coeruleus — the small cluster of neurons in the brainstem that is the brain's primary source of norepinephrine — goes nearly silent. The neuromodulator drops almost to zero. And this, it turns out, is precisely the condition that allows downscaling to occur. Without norepinephrine reinforcing the signal strength of every synaptic connection, the weakest connections lose their grip. They fade. The dream state provides the activation pattern that tests them. The absence of norepinephrine provides the chemical permission to let them go.                                                                                                               +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 You forget your dreams, in other words, because the same neurochemical environment that makes the forgetting of bad associations possible also makes it impossible to hold the dream in working memory long enough to report it. The mechanism of erasure and the mechanism of dream-forgetting are the same mechanism.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Crick was right in a way he could not have fully proven in 1983. The forgetting is not a side effect. The forgetting is the delivery.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 ## The noise that stays when the erasure doesn't work                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This reframe — dreams as deletion, forgetting as function — has a shadow side that is worth sitting with.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 If the purpose of REM sleep is to clear neural noise, what happens when REM sleep is disrupted? What happens when the erasure doesn't run?                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The answer, increasingly, appears to be something like the inverse of what Crick described. Instead of parasitic memories being weakened, they are left intact. Instead of spurious associations being dissolved, they harden. The clutter accumulates.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Researchers studying post-traumatic stress disorder have found that one of its defining neurological features is not merely the presence of traumatic memories but the inability to process them through the normal REM architecture. Matthew Walker's research at Berkeley, published across several papers between 2011 and 2021, suggests that REM sleep functions specifically as a form of overnight emotional therapy — and that when REM is interrupted before that process completes, the emotional charge attached to a memory remains undischarged. The memory is stored, but stored raw, without the attenuation that undisturbed REM normally provides.                                   +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This helps explain something that many people experience but rarely articulate: the specific quality of tiredness after a night of fragmented sleep, compared to a night of simply too little sleep. Total sleep deprivation leaves you dull, slow, fog-brained. Fragmented sleep — the kind where you drift in and out, where REM cycles are repeatedly interrupted — leaves you tender. Reactive. Small things feel large. Old grievances surface without warning. The emotional filing system is not merely underloaded; it is disorganized. Connections that should have been loosened overnight are still tight and pulling.                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 You have experienced this. The night you woke at 2am and never fully returned to sleep, and the next morning your husband said something mild and you felt a disproportionate flash of something that was not quite anger but was adjacent to it. That was noise in the system. That was the erasure that didn't run.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Researchers at the University of California, Berkeley, found in 2007 that after a single night of REM sleep deprivation, the amygdala — the brain's threat-detection center — showed 60 percent greater reactivity to negative images than it did after a full night of sleep. The prefrontal cortex, which normally regulates the amygdala's response, had partially decoupled from it. The brake had loosened. The noise was louder.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This is not a character flaw. It is a neurological consequence of a specific kind of sleep disruption. The brain has a system for managing its own emotional residue. When the system runs cleanly, you wake up with a kind of soft-edged equanimity that feels like grace but is actually neuroscience. When it doesn't, the noise carries forward into the day.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 ## Why this matters more after 50                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The cruel irony of what sleep research has uncovered about REM sleep and aging is this: the stage of sleep most responsible for emotional regulation, neural housekeeping, and the clearance of spurious associations is also the stage that deteriorates most reliably with age.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This is not a matter of debate. A 2004 paper by Christian Gillin at the University of California, San Diego — drawing on data from hundreds of sleep lab studies — documented that REM sleep begins declining in both duration and intensity from roughly the third decade of life, and the decline accelerates measurably after 50. By 65, most people are spending significantly less time in REM than they did at 35. The late REM cycles, which tend to occur in the final two hours of a normal sleep period, are the richest — the longest, the most emotionally active — and they are the ones most vulnerable to the fragmented, early-waking sleep pattern that becomes common after midlife.+
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This matters for the specific experience of waking at 3am. When you surface at 3am and cannot return to sleep, you are almost certainly cutting off the REM-rich second half of your night. The first half of the night is dominated by slow-wave sleep — deep, restorative, growth-hormone-releasing, physically reparative (covered in the Renewal pillar across earlier issues). The second half belongs to REM. So the 3am wake is not just costing you sleep. It is specifically costing you the stage of sleep that manages the emotional residue of your day, that edits the neural connections that should be loosened, that runs the clearing process that Crick described.                  +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Hormone shifts compound this. Estrogen has a complex relationship with REM architecture. Research by Barbara Moline and others through the 1990s and 2000s established that estrogen appears to support REM density — the richness of neural activity within REM periods. As estrogen declines during perimenopause and menopause, REM becomes shallower and more fragile. The erasure still runs, but it runs less deeply. Some of the noise that would have been cleared gets carried forward.                                                                                                                                                                                                      +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The result, over time, is cumulative. Not in the dramatic way of sleep deprivation studies, but in the quieter, more insidious way of a filing system that is never quite fully reorganized. You feel it not as exhaustion but as a low-grade emotional reactivity, a tendency to ruminate, a sense that things that should feel resolved do not quite feel resolved. Old patterns feel stickier. New learning feels harder to hold.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This is the mechanism beneath the experience. It is not vague or metaphorical. It is synaptic, specific, and, importantly, addressable.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 ## The one thing worth trying tonight                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 If the value of REM sleep lies in its completeness — if the erasure requires that the late cycles run without interruption — then the most targeted thing you can do is protect the back half of your night.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Not by sleeping more. By sleeping differently in the hours just before waking.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Here is the one thing: lower your body temperature in the 30 minutes before your typical wake time.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 This sounds counterintuitive. You are already awake, or nearly awake — why does temperature matter now? It matters because REM sleep is extraordinarily sensitive to body temperature. The brain cannot run its deepest, longest REM cycles if your core temperature is rising. And between roughly 4am and 6am, your body's natural thermogenesis — the process of generating heat ahead of waking — begins. If that process runs too fast, or if your environment is too warm, REM cycles that would otherwise extend and deepen get cut short. You surface.                                                                                                                                        +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 The intervention is simple. Keep your bedroom cooler than feels comfortable — research by the sleep scientist Matthew Walker and his Berkeley team points to 65 to 68 degrees Fahrenheit as the range in which REM architecture is most protected. If you cannot control your room temperature, try sleeping with lighter covers and allowing one foot to remain outside the blanket. The foot contains a dense network of blood vessels that are specifically used by the body to regulate core temperature; exposing it allows heat to dissipate without you becoming fully cold.                                                                                                                   +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 If you wake at 3am or 4am and feel the pull toward wakefulness — the spinning thoughts, the sudden alertness — resist turning on your phone. The light signals morning to the circadian system and begins suppressing the melatonin that is still trying to hold you in the second-half REM territory. Lie still. Keep your eyes closed. If your room is warm, push the covers down.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 You are trying to keep the conditions right for the final act of the night's work. The clearing is not done. The janitor is still in the building. The best thing you can do is leave the lights off and let the work finish.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 Crick did not have a prescription. He had a model. But models, when they are right, point you toward something actionable. This one says: the forgetting is the point. Protect the conditions in which the forgetting can happen. Let the brain do what it is trying to do.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           +
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       +
 You will wake up not remembering your dreams. That is not failure. That is the system working exactly as designed.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    +
